{"title":"Back Translation for Speech-to-text Translation Without Transcripts","domain":"SPEECH","seeds":[{"problem":"End-to-end speech-to-text translation (ST) without source transcripts cannot leverage ASR/MT pretraining and has limited parallel data. Directly generating source speech from target text for back-translation is hard due to short-to-long sequence generation and one-to-many speech variability.","method":"BT4ST: introduce self-supervised discrete speech units as an intermediate representation and synthesize source speech from target-side monolingual text by cascading (i) a Transformer target-to-unit model that predicts reduced discrete units (collapsing repeats) and (ii) a unit-to-speech HiFiGAN vocoder with a duration predictor and a speaker encoder. Discrete units are obtained from HuBERT features via K-means (e.g., K=100), which shortens sequences and disentangles content from pitch/speaker, easing generation. The synthesized pseudo ST data is then used to pre-train and fine-tune the ST model with real data, yielding on average +2.3 BLEU on MuST-C En→De/Fr/Es."},{"problem":"Synthetic speech-text pairs generated via back translation vary in quality; naively training on all can hurt ST performance, especially without transcripts.","method":"Train a unit-to-target model to translate generated units back to target text and score each synthetic sample by BLEU(ŷ,y); keep only the top ρ fraction (ρ=75% performs best) and discard the rest. Use a 2-stage schedule: pre-train the ST model on the selected synthetic data, then fine-tune on real ST data to mitigate noise. This filtering and training strategy improves MuST-C En→De from 26.2 to 26.6 BLEU at ρ=75% and underpins the overall +2.3 BLEU gains."},{"problem":"Single synthetic dataset may limit diversity in content and speaker characteristics, reducing the benefit of back-translated data.","method":"Diverse BT4ST: induce diversity by enabling dropout during beam decoding in the target-to-unit model and by randomly sampling speaker embeddings in the unit-to-speech model to generate multiple distinct pseudo datasets from the same monolingual text. Train separate ST models on each pseudo dataset and ensemble them by averaging token-level log probabilities at decode time. Ensembling five models yields an average +4.0 BLEU improvement across En→De/Fr/Es over the non-BT baseline."}]}
